data.description: Used to mark body of standing water, such as a lake or pond.
A single tree, often significant.
Forest. Sometimes considered to have restricted meaning "Woodland with no forestry".
The wetland tag is used for natural areas subject to inundation or with waterlogged ground
Uncultivated land covered with bushes or stunted trees.
Used to mark a coastline.
The top (summit) of a hill or mountain.
A vertical or almost vertical natural drop in terrain, usually with a bare rock surface.
A dwarf-shrub habitat, characterised by open, low growing woody vegetation, often dominated by plants of the Ericaceae.
Natural areas where the vegetation is dominated by grasses (Poaceae) and other herbaceous (non-woody) plants.
A notable rock or group of rocks, with at least one of them firmly attached to the underlying bedrock. See wiki for history and other meanings.
A line of trees
For areas of solid visible bedrock.
Area of shore which is fairly open, slopes smoothly to the water, and is free of trees
land within a water body. Redundant tag, should no longer be used.
An area covered by sand with no or very little vegetation
A spring is a point where water naturally surfaces
Area of water mostly surrounded by land.
An accumulation of loose angular rocks
A permanent body of ice formed naturally from snow that is moving under its own weight.
Used to tag a mountain or hill ridge
The entrance to a cave.
Use natural=wetland , wetland=marsh instead.
Habitat above tree line covered with grass, dwarf shrubs and mosses.
Large area covered with mud
A feature (rock, sandbar, coral, etc) lying beneath the surface of the water
A single notable freestanding rock, which may differ from the composition of the terrain it lies in.
A piece of elevated land sticking out into the sea or large lake.
A volcano is an opening exposed on the earth's surface where volcanic material is emitted.
An accumulation of rounded stones on a beach or riverbed
A large crack in a glacier
A valley
Don't use, see wikipage
A natural depression
Used to tag a peaked ridge.
